  "response_text": "World War I, also known as the Great War, was a complex conflict with multiple contributing factors. Historians generally agree that several key events and conditions led to its outbreak in 1914. When reflecting on which causes to emphasize and which to downplay, historians consider the significance of each factor in triggering the war and its broader impact on the global political landscape.\n\n### Main Causes Emphasized:\n\n1. **Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand**: This event is often cited as the immediate trigger for the war. The assassination of the heir to the Austro-Hungarian throne by a Serbian nationalist in Sarajevo on June 28, 1914, set off a chain reaction of diplomatic crises and mobilizations among European powers.\n\n2. **Alliances**: The complex system of alliances between European powers (the Triple Alliance and the Triple Entente) meant that a conflict in one part of Europe could quickly escalate into a full-scale war involving many nations",
